TY  - JOUR
T1  - A simple explanation of the relative performance evaluation puzzle
AU  - Celentani, Marco
AU  - Loveira, Rosa
JO  - Review of Economic Dynamics
VL  - 9
IS  - 3
SP  - 525
EP  - 540
PY  - 2006
DA  - 2006/07/01/
SN  - 1094-2025
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/j.red.2006.04.001
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1094202506000196
KW  - Relative performance evaluation
KW  - Optimal contracts
KW  - Executive compensation
AB  - We study a simple moral hazard model in which two risk-neutral owners establish incentives for their risk-averse managers to exert effort. Because the probability distributions over output realizations depend on a common aggregate shock, optimal contracts make the compensation of each manager contingent on own performance but also on a performance benchmark—the performance of the other firm. If the marginal return of effort depends on the aggregate state, optimal contracts are not monotonically decreasing in the performance benchmark. This provides a simple explanation of the Relative Performance Evaluation (RPE) Puzzle—the documented lack of a negative relationship between CEO compensation and comparative performance measures, such as industry or market performance. Our simple model can also explain one-sided RPE—the documented tendency to insulate a CEO's rewards from bad luck, but not from good luck. We clarify that our results are robust in several dimensions and we discuss other applications of our findings.
